<div class="skewDiv"></div>
<div class="finalYear">
    <h3 class="titleArts">Final Year</h3>
    <div class="desc">
        <div class="imageCollage">
            {{#each finalYear}}
            <img class="img{{@index}}" src= "/artsPortfolio/final/{{this}}" alt="">
            {{/each}}
        </div>
        <div class="projectInfo">
            <p>Glacier Abduction was the name of my final project. The inspiration came to me when I was helping out at an ice-cream store and I have accidentally left my water bottle in the freezer for too long.</p>
            <p>I wanted to take a different approach to my usual for this project. My focus for construction is usually on 2D pattern cutting however I cannot portray what I see in ice using this method. I had to keep in mind that the body is 3D and proceeded by draping fabrics on the mannequin. I wanted the raw but contained feel for my garments the same way as the ice looks fluid inside but bound by the borders of its casing.</p>
            <p>Like my construction, I decided to throw rigid rules (not the ones about safety) out the window and mix techniques plus use unusual tools. At the end I have gone for a texture print and a multi-layered screen print that was created using the continuous line technique to reflect my research.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="secondYear">
    <h3 class="titleArts">Second Year</h3>
    <div class="desc">
        <div class="firstHalfSecond">
            <div class="imageCollage">
                {{#each firstHalfSecond}}
                <img src= "/artsPortfolio/firstHalfSecond/{{this}}" alt="">
                {{/each}}
            </div>
            <div class="projectInfo">
                <p>This project was not only a group project but also a collaboration with <a href="http://www.missselfridge.com">Miss Selfridge.</a> During this project I had to research into competitors, find the customer profile, design, create and also the branding of the collection.</p>
                <p>The theme was water and initially I have looked at possible was of constructing the same feeling however I came into realisation that the brand is more into texture and prints rather than super unique construction. For this reason I have started thinking more about textile manipulation.</p>
                <p>My biggest inspiration came from my time in the water, specifically when I dive and look up to see the sunlight being reflected off the waves giving it the shine. This can be seen on the printed textile I have created.</p>
                <p>In terms of construction, I opted to choose an angled seam as this is not used incredibly often. and as the top has a bare back I decided to go for a double collar displaying shiny satin contrasting with the faux leather. For the bottom half, I have gone for shorts with a layer of pleated tul to act like a skirt.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="secondHalfSecond">
            <div class="imageCollage">
                {{#each secondHalfSecond}}
                <img src= "/artsPortfolio/secondHalfSecond/{{this}}" alt="">
                {{/each}}
            </div>
            <div class="projectInfo">
                <p>This time we chose our own inspiration. I like a good challenge and always was attracted to menswear. As I associate myself as more of a detail designer than extravagant shapes, this came no surprise to me.</p>
                <p>Sports affects a big chunk of my personal life and I viewed people as machines, where you need to eat well and exercise in order to be your optimal self. I was incredibly excited for the textile research that I had to conduct and I knew it was not easy to find the best fabrics when you are building a prototype. Keeping this in mind I still was able to find fabrics with breathability, wicking properties and also waterproof. I have researched into nano technologies and if I had more time would be thinking into incorporating code to create smart jackets.</p>
                <p>My research did not just stop at fabrics. I also looked into how the body exercise and even spoke to a sports physio to explain to me more about the human body. With this information I have proceeded to develop garments with cuts to help the body gain more from their exercise.</p>
                <p>As the fabrics were limited, I only had one hue to choose from, which was white do I have hand dyed the pieces myself. I also developed prints taking inspiration from machines and cars to print them on garments for safety as reflectives.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
